ref> His mother, Mary Kidman Foster, belonged to a prominent nonconformist family in Cambridgeshire,.<ref name=\"CWR 10-2-99 AlfD biog\" /> He was educated at [[Mill Hill School]] and at Rickmansworth. He married in 1877, Lydia Edith Death of Burnt Mill, Essex.<ref>Debrett's House of Commons 1901</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAt the age of seventeen, Davies left school and began working in the offices of a steamship company.<ref name=\"CWR 10-2-99 AlfD biog\" /> Within a few years he had started in business on his own account and proved very successful. He was founder and Chairman of Directors of Davies, Turner & Co., Ltd, London, Liverpool, and elsewhere. He was also President of Davies, Turner & Co., of New York, Boston, and Philadelphia, underwriters and international carriers.<ref>Who Was Who</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nHe was a [[Progressive Party (London)|Progressive party]] member of the [[London County Council]] from 1889-1892, representing [[Hackney North (UK Parliament constituency)|Hackney North]]. He earned a reputation as a social reformer, and at his own expense prosecuted a number of owners of unsanitary cellar dwellings.<ref name=\"CWR 10-2-99 AlfD biog\" />  In 1890, Davies was nominated to be Liberal candidate for the vacancy in [[East Carmarthenshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Carmarthenshire]] following the death of [[David Pugh (British politician)|David Pugh]] but he withdrew before the selection conference.<ref name=\"CJ 18-7-90 East Carms\">{{cite news|title=The Vacancy for East Carmarthenshire.|url=http://newspapers.library.wales/view/3761458/3761464/54|accessdate=8 December 2016|newspaper=Carmarthen Journal|date=18 July 1890|page=6}}</ref>\n\n==Member for Carmarthen Boroughs==\nIn 1899 he was selected as Liberal candidate for  [[Carmarthen (UK Parliament constituency)|Carmarthen Boroughs]], a constituency then held by the Liberal Unionist, Sir John Jones Jenkins. Davies defeated Jenkins at the 1900 General Election and sat as Liberal MP for the constituency until 1906.\n\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1900 United Kingdom general election|General election 1900]] [[Carmarthen (UK Parliament constituency)|Carmarthen District of Boroughs]]<ref>British parliamentary election results, 1885-1918 (Craig)</ref>\nElectorate 5,557}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Liberal Party (UK)\n |candidate = Alfred Davies\n |votes = 2,837\n |percentage = 58.1\n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Liberal Unionist Party (UK)\n |candidate = [[John Jenkins, 1st Baron Glantawe|John Jones Jenkins]]\n |votes =2,047\n |percentage = 41.9\n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n |votes = 790\n |percentage = 16.2\n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n |votes = \n |percentage = 87.9\n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n  |winner     = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |loser     = Liberal Unionist Party (UK)\n  |swing      = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\nDavies's time as member for the boroughs was eventful and a crisis arose over his differences with Lloyd George over the South African War.<ref name=\"CWR 4-10-07 AlfD obit\">{{cite news|title=Death of Mr Alfred Davies, of, Hampstead, London. Ex-M.P. for Carmarthen Boroughs.|url=http://newspapers.library.wales/view/3644780/3644782/10|accessdate=25 February 2017|newspaper=Carmarthen Weekly Reporter|date=4 October 1907|publisher=William Morgan Evans|page=2}}</ref> In 1903, when a General Election seemed imminent, some leading members of the Liberal association sought to remove Davies as candidate, with Tom Terrell and the former member for the constituency, Major E.R. Jones, being invited to address meetings.<ref name=\"CWR 4-10-07 AlfD obit\" /> Davies refused to participate in the selection process and this led to split in the ranks of the Liberal Association.<ref name=\"CWR 4-10-07 AlfD obit\" /> Ultimately, however, Davies withdrew in favour of [[W. Llewelyn Williams]].\n\nHe retired at the General Election of January 1906. He did not stand for parliament again.<ref>British parliamentary election results 1885-1918, Craig, F. W. S.</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n*Who Was Who\n*British parliamentary election results 1885-1918, Craig, F. W. S.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*Who Was Who; http://www.ukwhoswho.com\n*{{Find a Grave|6792437|Alfred Davies}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Carmarthen (UK Parliament constituency)|Carmarthen]]\n  | years  = [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]]&ndash;[[1906 United Kingdom general election|January 1906]]\n  | before = [[John Jenkins, 1st Baron Glantawe|Sir John Jones Jenkins]]\n  | after  = [[W. Llewelyn Williams]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, Alfred}}\n[[Category:1848 births]]\n[[Category:1907 deaths]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for Welsh constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:Members of London County Council]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Carmarthenshire constituencies]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1889-1892 \u2192 1889\u20131892 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Davies_(Carmarthen_MP)"}
{"title_page": "Henry Cautley, 1st Baron Cautley", "text_new": "'''Henry Strother Cautley, 1st Baron Cautley''' [[King's Counsel|KC]] (9 December 1863 \u2013 21 September 1946), known as '''Sir Henry Cautley, Bt''', from 1924 to 1936, was a [[United Kingdom|British]] barrister, judge and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician.\n\n==Background and education==\nCautley was the son of Henry Cautley and his wife Mary Ellen (n\u00e9e Strother). He was educated at [[Charterhouse School]] and [[King's College, Cambridge]], and was later called to the Bar, [[Middle Temple]].<ref>{{acad|id=CTLY881HS|name=Cautley, Henry Strother}}</ref>\n\n==Political and judicial career==\nHe soon turned to politics and unsuccessfully contested [[Dewsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Dewsbury]] in [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]] and [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895]]. However, in [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]] he was elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Leeds East (UK Parliament constituency)|Leeds East]]. Cautley lost this seat in 1906 when he was defeated by [[James O'Grady]] but returned to Parliament in [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910]] as MP for [[East Grinstead (UK Parliament constituency)|East Grinstead]], a seat he held until 1936. Apart from his political career he was also a [[Recorder (judge)|Recorder]] of [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]] from 1918 to 1935. He was made a [[King's Counsel]] in 1919 and created a '''Baronet''', of Horsted Keynes in the County of Sussex, in 1924.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=32918 |date=14 March 1924 |page=2229 }}</ref> On his retirement from the House of Commons in 1936 he was raised to the peerage as '''Baron Cautley''', of Lindfield in the County of Sussex.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=34307 |date=21 July 1936 |page=4670 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCautley married at St. Paul's Church, [[Woodhouse Eaves]], Leicestershire, on 1 October 1902, Alice Bohun Fox, daughter of B. H. C. Fox, JP, of Maplewell, Woodhouse Eaves;<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Marriages| day_of_week=Friday |date=3 October 1902 |page_number=1 |issue=36889}}</ref> they had no children. He died in 1946, aged 82, when the baronetcy and barony became extinct.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n* [http://thepeerage.com/p21159.htm The Peerage.com]\n\n==External links==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-henry-cautley | Henry Cautley }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Leeds East (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for Leeds East]]\n | years  = [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]] \u2013 [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]]\n | before = [[Thomas Leuty]]\n | after  = [[James O'Grady]]}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[East Grinstead (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for East Grinstead]]\n | years  = [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910]] \u2013 [[1936 East Grinstead by-election|1936]]\n | before = [[Charles Corbett]]\n | after  = [[Ralph Clarke (British politician)|Ralph Clarke]]\n}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-new | creation }}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Baron Cautley]] | years= 1936\u20131946 }}\n{{s-non | reason = Extinct }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cautley, Henry Cautley, 1st Baron}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1946 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Peers created by Edward VIII]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:People from Lindfield, West Sussex]]\n[[Category:People from Sunderland, Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:People from East Grinstead]]\n[[Category:Queen's Counsel 1901\u20132000]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1922\u20131923]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1924\u20131929]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1935\u20131945]]\n", "text_old": "'''Henry Strother Cautley, 1st Baron Cautley''' [[King's Counsel|KC]] (9 December 1863 \u2013 21 September 1946), known as '''Sir Henry Cautley, Bt''', from 1924 to 1936, was a [[United Kingdom|British]] barrister, judge and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician.\n\n==Background and education==\nCautley was the son of Henry Cautley and his wife Mary Ellen (n\u00e9e Strother). He was educated at [[Charterhouse School]] and [[King's College, Cambridge]], and was later called to the Bar, [[Middle Temple]].<ref>{{acad|id=CTLY881HS|name=Cautley, Henry Strother}}</ref>\n\n==Political and judicial career==\nHe soon turned to politics and unsuccessfully contested [[Dewsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Dewsbury]] in [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]] and [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895]]. However, in [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]] he was elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Leeds East (UK Parliament constituency)|Leeds East]]. Cautley lost this seat in 1906 when he was defeated by [[James O'Grady]] but returned to Parliament in [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910]] as MP for [[East Grinstead (UK Parliament constituency)|East Grinstead]], a seat he held until 1936. Apart from his political career he was also a [[Recorder (judge)|Recorder]] of [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]] from 1918 to 1935. He was made a [[King's Counsel]] in 1919 and created a '''Baronet''', of Horsted Keynes in the County of Sussex, in 1924.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=32918 |date=14 March 1924 |page=2229 }}</ref> On his retirement from the House of Commons in 1936 he was raised to the peerage as '''Baron Cautley''', of Lindfield in the County of Sussex.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=34307 |date=21 July 1936 |page=4670 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCautley married at St. Paul\u2032s Church, [[Woodhouse Eaves]], Leicestershire, on 1 October 1902, Alice Bohun Fox, daughter of B. H. C. Fox, JP, of Maplewell, Woodhouse Eaves;<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Marriages| day_of_week=Friday |date=3 October 1902 |page_number=1 |issue=36889}}</ref> they had no children. He died in 1946, aged 82, when the baronetcy and barony became extinct.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n* [http://thepeerage.com/p21159.htm The Peerage.com]\n\n==External links==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-henry-cautley | Henry Cautley }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Leeds East (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for Leeds East]]\n | years  = [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]] \u2013 [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]]\n | before = [[Thomas Leuty]]\n | after  = [[James O'Grady]]}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[East Grinstead (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for East Grinstead]]\n | years  = [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910]] \u2013 [[1936 East Grinstead by-election|1936]]\n | before = [[Charles Corbett]]\n | after  = [[Ralph Clarke (British politician)|Ralph Clarke]]\n}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-new | creation }}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Baron Cautley]] | years= 1936\u20131946 }}\n{{s-non | reason = Extinct }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cautley, Henry Cautley, 1st Baron}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1946 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]