egory:British sportsperson-politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1900-1914 \u2192 1900\u20131914", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Allen_(Stroud_MP)"}
{"title_page": "David Davis (Castellhywel)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n[[File:Portrait of Revd. David Davis (4673253) (cropped).jpg|thumb|200px|David Davis]]\n'''David Davis''' (14 February 1745 \u2013 3 July 1827), known as \"Castellhywel\" or \"Dafis Castellhywel\" to differentiate him from others of the same name, was a [[Wales|Welsh]] minister and poet.\n\nHe was born at Goetre Farm in [[Llangybi, Ceredigion|Llangybi]], [[Ceredigion|Cardiganshire]] and educated at [[Carmarthen Academy]].  He became a minister at Ciliau Aeron, where he married the local squire's daughter.  In about 1782 he moved to Castellhywel in the Cletwr valley, where he opened a [[school]].\n\n==Works==\n*''Cri Carcharor dan farn Marwolaeth'' (1792)\n*''Telyn Dewi'' (1824)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s-DAVI-DAV-1745.html Welsh Biography Online]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, David (Castellhywel)}}\n[[Category:1745 births]]\n[[Category:1827 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ceredigion]]\n[[Category:Welsh-language poets]]\n\n\n{{UK-poet-stub}}\n{{Wales-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n[[File:Portrait of Revd. David Davis (4673253) (cropped).jpg|thumb|200px|David Davis ]]\n'''David Davis''' (14 February 1745 \u2013 3 July 1827), known as \"Castellhywel\" or \"Dafis Castellhywel\" to differentiate him from others of the same name, was a [[Wales|Welsh]] minister and poet.\n\nHe was born at Goetre Farm in [[Llangybi, Ceredigion|Llangybi]], [[Ceredigion|Cardiganshire]] and educated at [[Carmarthen Academy]].  He became a minister at Ciliau Aeron, where he married the local squire's daughter.  In about 1782 he moved to Castellhywel in the Cletwr valley, where he opened a [[school]].\n\n==Works==\n*''Cri Carcharor dan farn Marwolaeth'' (1792)\n*''Telyn Dewi'' (1824)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s-DAVI-DAV-1745.html Welsh Biography Online]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, David (Castellhywel)}}\n[[Category:1745 births]]\n[[Category:1827 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ceredigion]]\n[[Category:Welsh-language poets]]\n\n\n{{UK-poet-stub}}\n{{Wales-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Davis_(Castellhywel)"}
{"title_page": "Sir John Ainsworth, 1st Baronet", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2014}}\n[[File:John Ainsworth.jpg|thumb|right|John Ainsworth]]\n[[File:Sir John Ainsworth Vanity Fair 7 Dec 1910.jpg|thumb|Sir John Ainsworth caricatured by \"WHO\" in ''Vanity Fair'', 1910]]\n'''Sir John Stirling Ainsworth''' (30 January 1844 \u2013 24 May 1923) was an English [[industrialist]], [[banker]] and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician.\n\n==Family and education==\nAinsworth was the son of Thomas Ainsworth of [[Cleator Moor]], [[Cumberland]]. His mother was Mary Laurie, daughter of John Stirling, a [[Doctor of Divinity]] from Craigie in [[East Ayrshire]]. He was educated at [[University College School]], London and at [[University College, London]] where he obtained [[Master of Arts|MA]] and [[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B]] degrees.<ref name=whowaswho>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> In 1879 he married Margaret Catherine daughter of Robert Reid Macredie. They had one son and two daughters. His wife died in 1918.<ref name=whowaswho/> His brother, [[David Ainsworth]] (1842\u20131906) was Liberal [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] for [[West Cumberland (UK Parliament constituency)|West Cumberland]] from 1880\u20131885 and for [[Egremont (UK Parliament constituency)|Egremont]] from 1892\u20131895.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/people/mr-david-ainsworth/index.html|title=Mr David Ainsworth|work=Hansard 1803\u20132005}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAinsworth had interests in the iron mines and related industries in Cumberland. He was Chairman of the [[Cleator and Workington Junction Railway]]. He was also involved in banking, being a director of the [[Whitehaven]] Joint Stock Bank <ref>''The Times House of Commons 1910''; Politico\u2019s Publishing 2004 p98</ref> which later merged with [[Westminster Bank|Parr's Bank]], of which Ainsworth then became director of the Cumberland and [[Westmorland|Westmoreland]] local board.<ref>The Times, 25 May 1923 p14</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nAinsworth contested the [[Barrow-in-Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow-in-Furness]] constituency at the [[1886 United Kingdom general election|1886 general election]]. He faced the sitting [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]], [[William Sproston Caine]] who had been elected earlier that year in a [[by-election]] as a Liberal but had switched to the [[Liberal Unionist Party]]. Ainsworth did not fight the general elections of [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]] or [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895]] but in [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]] he was chosen to contest [[Argyllshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Argyllshire]]. He did not win but got the chance to fight the seat again in 1903 at a [[by-election]] when the sitting member, Donald Ninian Nicol, died.  At the by-election, which was held on 26 August 1903, Ainsworth won in a straight fight against a Unionist candidate, Mr. C Stewart, by a majority of 1,586 votes.<ref>The Times, 29 August 1903 p8</ref> Whilst an MP he voted in favour of the 1908 Women's Enfranchisement Bill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1908/feb/28/womens-enfranchisement-bill-1|title=WOMEN'S ENFRANCHISEMENT BILL.|work=Hansard|date=28 February 1908|accessdate=}}</ref> He held the seat until [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]] when he stood down from Parliament.\n\n==Other public service==\nAinsworth was [[High Sheriff of Cumberland]] in 1891 <ref>The Times, 21 March 1891 p9</ref> and was later [[Deputy Lieutenant]] of Cumberland <ref>The Times, 22 December 1923 p11</ref> and of [[Argyllshire]].<ref>The Times, 25 May 1923 p 14</ref> He commanded the 3rd Volunteer Battalion, the [[Border Regiment]] from 1898\u20131902. He also served as a [[Justice of the Peace]] in Cumberland.<ref>The Times, 22 December 1923 p11</ref>  He was created a [[baronet]] in 1917.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=30017 |date=13 April 1917 |page=3493}}</ref><ref name=whowaswho/> In 1910 he was a member of the [[Royal Commission]] on Mines.<ref>The Times, 25 May 1923 p14</ref>\n\n==Death==\nAinsworth died on 24 May 1923 aged 79 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/people/sir-john-ainsworth/index.html|title=Sir John Ainsworth|work=Hansard 1803\u20132005}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ainsworth baronets]]\n*[[List of baronetcies in the baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n*[[List of Old Gowers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | sir-john-ainsworth | Sir John Ainsworth }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Argyllshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Argyllshire]]\n| years = [[1903 Argyllshire by-election|1903]] \u2013 [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]]\n| before = [[Donald Nicol (MP)]]\n| after = [[William Sutherland (Scottish politician)|William Sutherland]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ainsworth, John Stirling}}\n[[Category:1844 births]]\n[[Category:1923 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Cumberland]]\n[[Category:Scottish Liberal Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Highland constituencies]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:English bankers]]\n[[Category:English industrialists]]\n[[Category:People from Cleator Moor]]\n[[Category:Politics of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Politics of Cumbria]]\n[[Category:People educated at University College School]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Argyllshire]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Cumberland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2014}}\n[[File:John Ainsworth.jpg|thumb|right|John Ainsworth]]\n[[File:Sir John Ainsworth Vanity Fair 7 Dec 1910.jpg|thumb|Sir John Ainsworth caricatured by \"WHO\" in ''Vanity Fair'', 1910]]\n'''Sir John Stirling Ainsworth''' (30 January 1844 \u2013 24 May 1923) was an English [[industrialist]], [[banker]] and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician.\n\n==Family and education==\nAinsworth was the son of Thomas Ainsworth of [[Cleator Moor]], [[Cumberland]]. His mother was Mary Laurie, daughter of John Stirling, a [[Doctor of Divinity]] from Craigie in [[East Ayrshire]]. He was educated at [[University College School]], London and at [[University College, London]] where he obtained [[Master of Arts|MA]] and [[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B]] degrees.<ref name=whowaswho>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> In 1879 he married Margaret Catherine daughter of Robert Reid Macredie. They had one son and two daughters. His wife died in 1918.<ref name=whowaswho/> His brother, [[David Ainsworth]] (1842\u20131906) was Liberal [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] for [[West Cumberland (UK Parliament constituency)|West Cumberland]] from 1880\u20131885 and for [[Egremont (UK Parliament constituency)|Egremont]] from 1892-1895.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/people/mr-david-ainsworth/index.html|title=Mr David Ainsworth|work=Hansard 1803\u20132005}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAinsworth had interests in the iron mines and related industries in Cumberland. He was Chairman of the [[Cleator and Workington Junction Railway]]. He was also involved in banking, being a director of the [[Whitehaven]] Joint Stock Bank <ref>''The Times House of Commons 1910''; Politico\u2019s Publishing 2004 p98</ref> which later merged with [[Westminster Bank|Parr\u2019s Bank]], of which Ainsworth then became director of the Cumberland and [[Westmorland|Westmoreland]] local board.<ref>The Times, 25 May 1923 p14</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nAinsworth contested the [[Barrow-in-Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow-in-Furness]] constituency at the [[1886 United Kingdom general election|1886 general election]]. He faced the sitting [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]], [[William Sproston Caine]] who had been elected earlier that year in a [[by-election]] as a Liberal but had switched to the [[Liberal Unionist Party]]. Ainsworth did not fight the general elections of [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]] or [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895]] but in [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]] he was chosen to contest [[Argyllshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Argyllshire]]. He did not win but got the chance to fight the seat again in 1903 at a [[by-election]] when the sitting member, Donald Ninian Nicol, died.  At the by-election, which was held on 26 August 1903, Ainsworth won in a straight fight against a Unionist candidate, Mr. C Stewart, by a majority of 1,586 votes.<ref>The Times, 29 August 1903 p8</ref> Whilst an MP he voted in favour of the 1908 Women's Enfranchisement Bill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1908/feb/28/womens-enfranchisement-bill-1|title=WOMEN'S ENFRANCHISEMENT BILL.|work=Hansard|date=28 February 1908|accessdate=}}</ref> He held the seat until [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]] when he stood down from Parliament.\n\n==Other public service==\nAinsworth was [[High Sheriff of Cumberland]] in 1891 <ref>The Times, 21 March 1891 p9</ref> and was later [[Deputy Lieutenant]] of Cumberland <ref>The Times, 22 December 1923 p11</ref> and of [[Argyllshire]].<ref>The Times, 25 May 1923 p 14</ref> He commanded the 3rd Volunteer Battalion, the [[Border Regiment]] from 1898-1902. He also served as a [[Justice of the Peace]] in Cumberland.<ref>The Times, 22 December 1923 p11</ref>  He was created a [[baronet]] in 1917.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=30017 |date=13 April 1917 |page=3493}}</ref><ref name=whowaswho/> In 1910 he was a member of the [[Royal Commission]] on Mines.<ref>The Times, 25 May 1923 p14</ref>\n\n==Death==\nAinsworth died on 24 May 1923 aged 79 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/people/sir-john-ainsworth/index.html|title=Sir John Ainsworth|work=Hansard 1803\u20132005}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ainsworth baronets]]\n*[[List of baronetcies in the baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n*[[List of Old Gowers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | sir-john-ainsworth | Sir John Ainsworth }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Argyllshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Argyllshire]]\n| years = [[1903 Argyllshire by-election|1903]] \u2013 [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]]\n| before = [[Donald Nicol (MP)]]\n| after = [[William Sutherland (Scottish politician)|William Sutherland]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ainsworth, John Stirling}}\n[[Category:1844 births]]\n[[Category:1923 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Cumberland]]\n[[Category:Scottish Liberal Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Highland constituencies]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:English bankers]]\n[[Category:English industrialists]]\n[[Category:People from Cleator Moor]]\n[[Category:Politics of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Politics of Cumbria]]\n[[Category:People educated at University College School]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Argyllshire]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Cumberland]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's, 1892-1895 \u2192 1892\u20131895 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_John_Ainsworth,_1st_Baronet"}
{"title_page": "Martin White (politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n'''James Martin White''' (usually known to as '''Martin White''' or  '''J. Martin White''') (1858 \u2013 7 July 1928)<ref>Death registers, Scotland, http://www.scotlandspeople.gov.uk</ref> was a wealthy [[Scotland|Scottish]] businessman and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician. He also took a keen interest in the establishment of the scientific study of [[sociology]] in association with his boyhood friend [[Patrick Geddes]] and was an enthusiastic supporter of the development of the [[pipe organ]].\n\nWhite was born in [[New York City]], the son of wealthy jute merchant James Farquhar White and his wife Elizabeth Grundy.  White Sr. had, in 1849, established a 'dry goods' company, J F White & Co. in New York selling all kinds of imported and domestic textiles.<ref>Financial Review USA, 24 Aug 1897</ref> However, with the onset of the American Civil War he had returned home to Scotland and leased [[Castle Huntly]], [[Perthshire]] as the family home. In 1880 they bought and moved to a baronial castle at [[Balruddery]], [[Angus, Scotland|Angus]], near the city of [[Dundee]].<ref name=soco>{{cite web | title=Biographical Database | url=https://sites.google.com/site/sociologysource/thebranfordproject2/thebranfordproject3 | work=Envisioning Sociology: Victor Branford, Patrick Geddes, and Social Reconstruction|author=[[John Scott (sociologist)|John Scott]] and Ray Bromley | publisher= SUNY Press| year=2013 }}</ref> Ran his family business from Dundee and New York, but took a back seat to pursue political and scientific interests.\n\nJ Martin White studied engineering at Cassel in Germany and was very interested in the technological innovations of his time, becoming chairman of the Dundee Technical Institute. He was a keen photographer and had his own darkroom from the late 1870s.  In April 1881 he and his father, James F White, installed electricity at their house, Balruddery by Longforgan, outside Dundee.  They generated the electricity with a Siemens SDJ Shuntwound 50-volt dynamo driven by a turbine on a stream on the estate<ref>The Electrician, 22 Jan 1886</ref> and thus established probably the first domestic generating plant in Scotland and the second, after Cragside, in Britain.  \nMartin White was also a collector and connoisseur of Japanese art.<ref>Dundee Free Library Report, June 1898</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nBy the 1890s White had become increasingly wealthy through the family business, J F White & Co.<ref name=soco/>\n\nHe first stood for Parliament at the [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892 general election]], when he unsuccessfully contested [[St Andrews Burghs (UK Parliament constituency)|St Andrews Burghs]].<ref name=\"craig1885-1918\">{{cite book\n |last=Craig\n |first=F. W. S.\n |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig\n |title=British parliamentary election results 1885\u20131918\n |origyear=1974\n |edition= 2nd\n |year=1989\n |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services\n |location=Chichester\n |isbn= 0-900178-27-2\n |page=519\n}}</ref> When the Liberal member of parliament for [[Forfar (UK Parliament constituency)|Forfarshire]], [[John Rigby (politician)|Sir John Rigby]] was appointed a [[Lord Justice of Appeal]] in 1894, it was expected that White would be the party's candidate at the ensuing [[1894 Forfarshire by-election|by-election]]. However, a London-based stock-broker, Henry Robson was chosen, with the result that the seat was lost to the [[Liberal Unionist Party|Liberal Unionists]].<ref name=times>{{cite news |title=Election Intelligence: Forfarshire |work=[[The Times]] |page=6 |date=20 November 1894 }}</ref>\n\nA [[1895 United Kingdom general election|general election was held in the following year]], and on this occasion White was chosen to contest the seat. He regained the seat comfortably for the Liberals, with a majority of 441 votes.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Polls |work=[[The Times]] |page=6 |date=23 July 1895 }}</ref>\n\nHis membership of the [[United Kingdom House of Commons|Commons]] was to be brief, however. Following weeks of rumours, the ''Dundee Advertiser'' reported on 14 November 1896 that he had resigned his seat. This was initially denied by his private secretary, who stated that he simply gone to India on business, and expected to return for the opening of parliament.<ref>{{cite news |title=Election Intelligence |work=[[The Times]] |page=10 |date=16 November 1896 }}</ref> However, on 20 November, the executive committee of the Forfarshire Liberal Association received an angry letter from White. In it, he stated that he had not intended to resign. However he felt the story had been inserted in the ''Advertiser'' by members of the committee, and this act of disloyalty meant that he no longer had any obligations to the party. Accordingly, he resigned his seat,<ref>{{cite news |title=Election Intelligence |work=[[The Times]] |page=8 |date=21 November 1896 }}</ref> by accepting appointment as [[Steward of the Chiltern Hundreds]].<ref name=\"hoc-resignations\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04731.pdf \n |title=Appointments to the Chiltern Hundreds and Manor of Northstead Stewardships since 1850 \n |author=Department of Information Services \n |publisher=[[House of Commons Library]] \n |date=14 January 2010 \n |accessdate=13 August 2010 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615142225/http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04731.pdf \n |archivedate=15 June 2010 \n}}</ref> The reason for the rumours circulating in Dundee and for his resignation were that a court case for breach of promise to marry had been brought by clergyman's daughter Helen Grant. She and White had known each other from the age of twelve and had had a longstanding affair. Ella Grant claimed that she had become pregnant and had refused the abortion that had been suggested by White. White made an out-of-cort settlement and the case never became public knowledge at the time.<ref>Summons of Miss Helen or Ella Guillan Grant, 1896, National Archives\nof Scotland NAS02023 CS248\u20112390/1.</ref>\n\nWhite was subsequently chosen as prospective Liberal candidate for the [[Wilton (UK Parliament constituency)|Wilton Division of Wiltshire]]. However, when a [[1900 Wilton by-election|by-election]] occurred in July 1900, the [[Second Boer War]] was in progress. The party decided not to contest the seat, allowing [[James Archibald Morrison|James Morrison]], an army officer, invalided from the front in South Africa, to be returned unopposed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Election Intelligence |work=[[The Times]] |page=10 |date=13 June 1900 }}</ref>  At the [[1900 United Kingdom general election|general election in October 1900]], White did contest Wilton, but Morrison held the seat with a majority of 841 votes (12.6% of the total).<ref name=\"craig-wilton\">Craig, page 418</ref>\n\nAt the [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 general election]], he failed to be elected at [[Great Yarmouth (UK Parliament constituency)|Great Yarmouth]]. He lodged an [[election petition]],<ref name=\"times-1906-petition-lodged\">{{cite news\n|title=An election petition at Yarmouth\n|date=12 February 1906\n|work=[[The Times]]\n|pages=10, col B\n|location=London\n}}</ref> attempting to have the result overturned due to alleged bribery, treating and illegal payments by his Conservative opponent [[Arthur Fell]].<ref name=\"times-1906-petition-lodged\" /> The election court found that treating and bribery had indeed taken place, but the two judges sitting on the case did not agree whether Fell was responsible for the actions of a Mr Baker who was found to have had acted illegally.<ref name=\"times-leader-curious\">{{cite news\n|title=The trial of the Yarmouth election petition has come to a curious conclusion\n|date=5 May 1906\n|work=[[The Times]]\n|pages=11, col D\n|location=London\n}}</ref> The first judge, Justice Channell, held that Baker was acting as an agent of Fell; but the more senior judge, [[William Grantham|Justice Grantham]], held that Fell was not responsible,<ref name=\"times-leader-curious\" /> and the petition was therefore dismissed.<ref name=\"times-leader-curious\" />  However, the outcome was widely denounced as perverse, and was one of a series of election petition judgments in which Grantham (himself a former Conservative MP) was seen to have acted in a partisan manner.<ref name=\"times-grantham-obit\">{{cite news\n|title=Death Of Mr. Justice Grantham. A Vigorous Personality\n|date=1 December 1911\n|work=[[The Times]]\n|pages=11, col E\n|location=London}}</ref> The judgment in the Yarmouth petition was the subject of a debate in the Commons in July 1906<ref name=\"yarmouth-petition-debate\">{{cite hansard | house=House of Commons | url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1906/jul/06/yarmouth-election-petition |title=Yarmouth Election Petition | date =6 July 1906 |volume=160 | column = cc369-414 }}</ref> in which Grantham's partisanship was widely condemned.<ref name=\"times-grantham-censure-debate\">{{cite news\n|title=House Of Commons: The Yarmouth election petition\n|date=7 July 1906\n|work=The Times\n|pages=4, col E\n|location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Academic endowments and Philanthropy==\nWhite developed a close friendship with [[Patrick Geddes]], and endowed a chair of botany for him at [[University of Dundee|University College Dundee]]. Geddes was developing the field of [[sociology]], and White began generously funding the teaching of the subject at the [[University of London]].<ref>{{cite news |title=University Intelligence |work=[[The Times]] |page=10 |date=13 May 1904}}</ref> He eventually provided an endowment to create a Department of Sociology at the university.<ref>Scott, John and Bromley, Ray 2013. ''Envisioning Sociology: Victor Branford, Patrick Geddes, and Social Reconstruction''New York: SUNY Press: p 32.</ref>\nA lifelong philanthropist, each July and August for over 15 years he turned a farmhouse on the estate into a holiday camp for poor and disabled children from the slums of Dundee, enabling over 200 children a year to benefit from two weeks of clean air, healthy outdoor activities and good food. \nIn 1892 he limited outdoor labourers on his estate to a 9-hour day, granting them also a half-day on Saturdays and a week's annual holiday.<ref>Obituary, The Dundee Courier and Advertiser 9 July 1928</ref>  In 1903 he instituted a pension scheme for all employees on the Balruddery Estate.<ref>Dundee Advertiser, 9 April 1903</ref> \nSome of the many other organisations benefiting from his largesse included the Scottish Amateur Gymnastics Association, St Andrew's University, Dundee Medical School and  Dundee Technical Institute.\n\n==Development of the pipe organ==\nWhite developed a love of the pipe organ, becoming an expert on the instrument, and president of the [[Organ Club]]. He financially supported [[Robert Hope-Jones]] in his development of the [[theatre organ]]. In the central hall at Balruddery he had installed an organ that, originally built by Casson and voiced by Thynne, had been reconstructed by Hope-Jones with electric action, double and pizzicato touches and some new stops. In 1913, George Laing Miller, in ''The Recent Revolution in Organ Building'' wrote:\n<blockquote>Mr White... has managed to devote much time and thought to the art of organ playing and organ building...All honor to Martin White! <ref>{{cite book |title=The Recent Revolution in Organ Building, Being an Account of Modern Developments |last=Miller |first=George Laing |authorlink= |year=1913 |location= |isbn= |page=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.75964/page/n136 136] |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.75964|accessdate= }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Family life==\nWhite was married twice. On 6 August 1898 he married Mary MacRae, a watercolourist, and they had two children. Due to his infidelity the marriage broke down in 1906, and the couple were divorced in 1912.<ref name=soco/> Mary MacRae White went on to be a successful artist in the United States.\n\nIn 1913 he married Alice (Priscilla) Frost, a widow.\n\n==Death==\nJ Martin White died suddenly at Balruddery in July 1928.<ref>{{cite news |title=Deaths |work=[[The Times]] |page=1 |date=10 July 1928}}</ref> He was buried locally, with a monument to his memory erected in [[Liff, Angus|Liff]] Parish Church.<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num= LB13217 |desc= LIFF, PARISH CHURCH, WATT/WEBSTER MEMORIAL|cat=B |access-date=27 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=33em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-james-white-1 | Martin White}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | before = [[Charles Maule Ramsay]]\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Forfarshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Forfarshire]]\n | years  = [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895]] \u2013 [[1897 Forfarshire by-election|1897]]\n | after  = [[John Sinclair, 1st Baron Pentland|John Sinclair]] \n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:White, James Martin}}\n[[Category:1857 births]]\n[[Category:1928 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish Liberal Party MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:Scottish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Dundee]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n'''James Martin White''' (usually known to as '''Martin White''' or  '''J. Martin White''') (1858 \u2013 7 July 1928)<ref>Death registers, Scotland, http://www.scotlandspeople.gov.uk</ref> was a wealthy [[Scotland|Scottish]] businessman and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician. He also took a keen interest in the establishment of the scientific study of [[sociology]] in association with his boyhood friend [[Patrick Geddes]] and was an enthusiastic supporter of the development of the [[pipe organ]].\n\nWhite was born in [[New York City]], the son of wealthy jute merchant James Farquhar White and his wife Elizabeth Grundy.  White Sr. had, in 1849, established a 'dry goods' company, J F White & Co. in New York selling all kinds of imported and domestic textiles.<ref>Financial Review USA, 24 Aug 1897</ref> However, with the onset of the American Civil War he had returned home to Scotland and leased [[Castle Huntly]], [[Perthshire]] as the family home. In 1880 they bought and moved to a baronial castle at [[Balruddery]], [[Angus, Scotland|Angus]], near the city of [[Dundee]].<ref name=soco>{{cite web | title=Biographical Database | url=https://sites.google.com/site/sociologysource/thebranfordproject2/thebranfordproject3 | work=Envisioning Sociology: Victor Branford, Patrick Geddes, and Social Reconstruction|author=[[John Scott (sociologist)|John Scott]] and Ray Bromley | publisher= SUNY Press| year=2013 }}</ref> Ran his family business from Dundee and New York, but took a back seat to pursue political and scientific interests.\n\nJ Martin White studied engineering at Cassel in Germany and was very interested in the technological innovations of his time, becoming chairman of the Dundee Technical Institute. He was a keen photographer and had his own darkroom from the late 1870s.  In April 1881 he and his father, James F White, installed electricity at their house, Balruddery by Longforgan, outside Dundee.  They generated the electricity with a Siemens SDJ Shuntwound 50-volt dynamo driven by a turbine on a stream on the estate<ref>The Electrician, 22 Jan 1886</ref> and thus established probably the first domestic generating plant in Scotland and the second, after Cragside, in Britain.  \nMartin White was also a collector and connoisseur of Japanese art.<ref>Dundee Free Library Report, June 1898</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nBy the 1890s White had become increasingly wealthy through the family business, J F White & Co.<ref name=soco/>\n\nHe first stood for Parliament at the [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892 general election]], when he unsuccessfully contested [[St Andrews Burghs (UK Parliament constituency)|St Andrews Burghs]].<ref name=\"craig1885-1918\">{{cite book\n |last=Craig\n |first=F. W. S.\n |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig\n |title=British parliamentary election results 1885\u20131918\n |origyear=1974\n |edition= 2nd\n |year=1989\n |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services\n |location=Chichester\n |isbn= 0-900178-27-2\n |page=519\n}}</ref> When the Liberal member of parliament for [[Forfar (UK Parliament constituency)|Forfarshire]], [[John Rigby (politician)|Sir John Rigby]] was appointed a [[Lord Justice of Appeal]] in 1894, it was expected that White would be the party's candidate at the ensuing [[1894 Forfarshire by-election|by-election]]. However, a London-based stock-broker, Henry Robson was chosen, with the result that the seat was lost to the [[Liberal Unionist Party|Liberal Unionists]].<ref name=times>{{cite news |title=Election Intelligence: Forfarshire |work=[[The Times]] |page=6 |date=20 November 1894 }}</ref>\n\nA [[1895 United Kingdom general election|general election was held in the following year]], and on this occasion White was chosen to contest the seat. He regained the seat comfortably for the Liberals, with a majority of 441 votes.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Polls |work=[[The Times]] |page=6 |date=23 July 1895 }}</ref>\n\nHis membership of the [[United Kingdom House of Commons|Commons]] was to be brief, however. Following weeks of rumours, the ''Dundee Advertiser'' reported on 14 November 1896 that he had resigned his seat. This was initially denied by his private secretary, who stated that he simply gone to India on business, and expected to return for the opening of parliament.<ref>{{cite news |title=Election Intelligence |work=[[The Times]] |page=10 |date=16 November 1896 }}</ref> However, on 20 November, the executive committee of the Forfarshire Liberal Association received an angry letter from White. In it, he stated that he had not intended to resign. However he felt the story had been inserted in the ''Advertiser'' by members of the committee, and this act of disloyalty meant that he no longer had any obligations to the party. Accordingly, he resigned his seat,<ref>{{cite news |title=Election Intelligence |work=[[The Times]] |page=8 |date=21 November 1896 }}</ref> by accepting appointment as [[Steward of the Chiltern Hundreds]].<ref name=\"hoc-resignations\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04731.pdf \n |title=Appointments to the Chiltern Hundreds and Manor of Northstead Stewardships since 1850 \n |author=Department of Information Services \n |publisher=[[House of Commons Library]] \n |date=14 January 2010 \n |accessdate=13 August 2010 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615142225/http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04731.pdf \n |archivedate=15 June 2010 \n}}</ref> The reason for the rumours circulating in Dundee and for his resignation were that a court case for breach of promise to marry had been brought by clergyman\u2019s daughter Helen Grant. She and White had known each other from the age of twelve and had had a longstanding affair. Ella Grant claimed that she had become pregnant and had refused the abortion that had been suggested by White. White made an out-of-cort settlement and the case never became public knowledge at the time.<ref>Summons of Miss Helen or Ella Guillan Grant, 1896, National Archives\nof Scotland NAS02023 CS248\u20112390/1.</ref>\n\nWhite was subsequently chosen as prospective Liberal candidate for the [[Wilton (UK Parliament constituency)|Wilton Division of Wiltshire]]. However, when a [[1900 Wilton by-election|by-election]] occurred in July 1900, the [[Second Boer War]] was in progress. The party decided not to contest the seat, allowing [[James Archibald Morrison|James Morrison]], an army officer, invalided from the front in South Africa, to be returned unopposed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Election Intelligence |work=[[The Times]] |page=10 |date=13 June 1900 }}</ref>  At the [[1900 United Kingdom general election|general election in October 1900]], White did contest Wilton, but Morrison held the seat with a majority of 841 votes (12.6% of the total).<ref name=\"craig-wilton\">Craig, page 418</ref>\n\nAt the [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906 general election]], he failed to be elected at [[Great Yarmouth (UK Parliament constituency)|Great Yarmouth]]. He lodged an [[election petition]],<ref name=\"times-1906-petition-lodged\">{{cite news\n|title=An election petition at Yarmouth\n|date=12 February 1906\n|work=[[The Times]]\n|pages=10, col B\n|location=London\n}}</ref> attempting to have the result overturned due to alleged bribery, treating and illegal payments by his Conservative opponent [[Arthur Fell]].<ref name=\"times-1906-petition-lodged\" /> The election court found that treating and bribery had indeed taken place, but the two judges sitting on the case did not agree whether Fell was responsible for the actions of a Mr Baker who was found to have had acted illegally.<ref name=\"times-leader-curious\">{{cite news\n|title=The trial of the Yarmouth election petition has come to a curious conclusion\n|date=5 May 1906\n|work=[[The Times]]\n|pages=11, col D\n|location=London\n}}</ref> The first judge, Justice Channell, held that Baker was acting as an agent of Fell; but the more senior judge, [[William Grantham|Justice Grantham]], held that Fell was not responsible,<ref name=\"times-leader-curious\" /> and the petition was therefore dismissed.<ref name=\"times-leader-curious\" />  However, the outcome was widely denounced as perverse, and was one of a series of election petition judgments in which Grantham (himself a former Conservative MP) was seen to have acted in a partisan manner.<ref name=\"times-grantham-obit\">{{cite news\n|title=Death Of Mr. Justice Grantham. A Vigorous Personality\n|date=1 December 1911\n|work=[[The Times]]\n|pages=11, col E\n|location=London}}</ref> The judgment in the Yarmouth petition was the subject of a debate in the Commons in July 1906<ref name=\"yarmouth-petition-debate\">{{cite hansard | house=House of Commons | url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1906/jul/06/yarmouth-election-petition |title=Yarmouth Election Petition | date =6 July 1906 |volume=160 | column = cc369-414 }}</ref> in which Grantham's partisanship was widely condemned.<ref name=\"times-grantham-censure-debate\">{{cite news\n|title=House Of Commons: The Yarmouth election petition\n|date=7 July 1906\n|work=The Times\n|pages=4, col E\n|location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Academic endowments and Philanthropy==\nWhite developed a close friendship with [[Patrick Geddes]], and endowed a chair of botany for him at [[University of Dundee|University College Dundee]]. Geddes was developing the field of [[sociology]], and White began generously funding the teaching of the subject at the [[University of London]].<ref>{{cite news |title=University Intelligence |work=[[The Times]] |page=10 |date=13 May 1904}}</ref> He eventually provided an endowment to create a Department of Sociology at the university.<ref>Scott, John and Bromley, Ray 2013. ''Envisioning Sociology: Victor Branford, Patrick Geddes, and Social Reconstruction''New York: SUNY Press: p 32.</ref>\nA lifelong philanthropist, each July and August for over 15 years he turned a farmhouse on the estate into a holiday camp for poor and disabled children from the slums of Dundee, enabling over 200 children a year to benefit from two weeks of clean air, healthy outdoor activities and good food. \nIn 1892 he limited outdoor labourers on his estate to a 9-hour day, granting them also a half-day on Saturdays and a week's annual holiday.<ref>Obituary, The Dundee Courier and Advertiser 9 July 1928</ref>  In 1903 he instituted a pension scheme for all employees on the Balruddery Estate.<ref>Dundee Advertiser, 9 April 1903</ref> \nSome of the many other organisations benefiting from his largesse included the Scottish Amateur Gymnastics Association, St Andrew's University, Dundee Medical School and  Dundee Technical Institute.\n\n==Development of the pipe organ==\nWhite developed a love of the pipe organ, becoming an expert on the instrument, and president of the [[Organ Club]]. He financially supported [[Robert Hope-Jones]] in his development of the [[theatre organ]]. In the central hall at Balruddery he had installed an organ that, originally built by Casson and voiced by Thynne, had been reconstructed by Hope-Jones with electric action, double and pizzicato touches and some new stops. In 1913, George Laing Miller, in ''The Recent Revolution in Organ Building'' wrote:\n<blockquote>Mr White... has managed to devote much time and thought to the art of organ playing and organ building...All honor to Martin White! <ref>{{cite book |title=The Recent Revolution in Organ Building, Being an Account of Modern Developments |last=Miller |first=George Laing |authorlink= |year=1913 |location= |isbn= |page=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.75964/page/n136 136] |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.75964|accessdate= }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Family life==\nWhite was married twice. On 6 August 1898 he married Mary MacRae, a watercolourist, and they had two children. Due to his infidelity the marriage broke down in 1906, and the couple were divorced in 1912.<ref name=soco/> Mary MacRae White went on to be a successful artist in the United States.\n\nIn 1913 he married Alice (Priscilla) Frost, a widow.\n\n==Death==\nJ Martin White died suddenly at Balruddery in July 1928.<ref>{{cite news |title=Deaths |work=[[The Times]] |page=1 |date=10 July 1928}}</ref> He was buried locally, with a monument to his memory erected in [[Liff, Angus|Liff]] Parish Church.<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num= LB13217 |desc= LIFF, PARISH CHURCH, WATT/WEBSTER MEMORIAL|cat=B |access-date=27 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=33em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-james-white-1 | Martin White}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | before = [[Charles Maule Ramsay]]\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Forfarshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Forfarshire]]\n | years  = [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895]] \u2013 [[1897 Forfarshire by-election|1897]]\n | after  = [[John Sinclair, 1st Baron Pentland|John Sinclair]] \n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:White, James Martin}}\n[[Category:1857 births]]\n[[Category:1928 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish Liberal Party MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:Scottish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Dundee]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eParliamentary career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_White_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "Robert Ward (British politician)", "text_new": "{{Other people|Robert Ward}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n[[File:Robert Ward.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Ward in 1895.]]\n[[Captain (land)|Captain]] [[The Honourable]] ''' Robert Arthur Ward''', [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (23 February 1871 \u2013 14 June 1942), was a British soldier and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician.\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Acheson Sisters (Ladies Alexandra, Mary and Theo Acheson).jpg|thumb|left|Acheson Sisters (Ladies Alexandra, Mary and Theo Acheson), [[John Singer Sargent]], 1902]]\n\nWard was the third son of [[William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley]], and his second wife Georgina Elisabeth, daughter of Sir Thomas Moncreiffe, 7th Baronet. [[William Ward, 2nd Earl of Dudley]], was his elder brother.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\">[http://www.thepeerage.com/p282.htm#i2814 thepeerage.com Hon. Robert Arthur Ward]</ref> He was returned to Parliament for [[Crewe (UK Parliament constituency)|Crewe]] in the [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895 general election]], a seat he held until 1900.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/><ref>{{Rayment-hc|c|6|date=March 2012}}</ref>\n\nWard fought in the [[Matabeleland]] campaign of 1896. He served with the 4th Battalion, [[Imperial Yeomanry]], in the [[Second Boer War]] from early 1900 until he resigned his commission 5 March 1902,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27418 |page=1962 |date=21 March 1902}}</ref> when he was appointed a [[second lieutenant]] of the [[Worcestershire Yeomanry|Worcestershire Yeomanry (The Queen's Own Worcestershire Hussars)]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27419 |date=25 March 1902 |page=2081 }}</ref> He later served in the [[First World War]], where he was twice [[mentioned in despatches]]. In 1919 he was appointed an Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (OBE).<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\nWard married Lady Mary Acheson, daughter of [[Archibald Acheson, 4th Earl of Gosford]] and his wife [[Louisa Acheson, Countess of Gosford|Lady Louisa Montagu]], in 1906. He died in June 1942, aged 71.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{hansard-contribs | hon-robert-ward | Robert Ward }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Crewe (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for Crewe]]\n | years  = [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895]]\u2013[[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]]\n | before = [[Walter McLaren]]\n | after  = [[James Tomkinson]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ward, Robert}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n[[Category:Younger sons of earls]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Ward family|Robert]]\n[[Category:Worcestershire Yeomanry officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Robert Ward}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n[[File:Robert Ward.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Ward in 1895.]]\n[[Captain (land)|Captain]] [[The Honourable]] ''' Robert Arthur Ward''', [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (23 February 1871 \u2013 14 June 1942), was a British soldier and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician.\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Acheson Sisters (Ladies Alexandra, Mary and Theo Acheson).jpg|thumb|left|Acheson Sisters (Ladies Alexandra, Mary and Theo Acheson), [[John Singer Sargent]], 1902]]\n\nWard was the third son of [[William Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley]], and his second wife Georgina Elisabeth, daughter of Sir Thomas Moncreiffe, 7th Baronet. [[William Ward, 2nd Earl of Dudley]], was his elder brother.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\">[http://www.thepeerage.com/p282.htm#i2814 thepeerage.com Hon. Robert Arthur Ward]</ref> He was returned to Parliament for [[Crewe (UK Parliament constituency)|Crewe]] in the [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895 general election]], a seat he held until 1900.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/><ref>{{Rayment-hc|c|6|date=March 2012}}</ref>\n\nWard fought in the [[Matabeleland]] campaign of 1896. He served with the 4th Battalion, [[Imperial Yeomanry]], in the [[Second Boer War]] from early 1900 until he resigned his commission 5 March 1902,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27418 |page=1962 |date=21 March 1902}}</ref> when he was appointed a [[second lieutenant]] of the [[Worcestershire Yeomanry|Worcestershire Yeomanry (The Queen\u00b4s Own Worcestershire Hussars)]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27419 |date=25 March 1902 |page=2081 }}</ref> He later served in the [[First World War]], where he was twice [[mentioned in despatches]]. In 1919 he was appointed an Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (OBE).<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\nWard married Lady Mary Acheson, daughter of [[Archibald Acheson, 4th Earl of Gosford]] and his wife [[Louisa Acheson, Countess of Gosford|Lady Louisa Montagu]], in 1906. He died in June 1942, aged 71.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{hansard-contribs | hon-robert-ward | Robert Ward }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Crewe (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for Crewe]]\n | years  = [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895]]\u2013[[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]]\n | before = [[Walter McLaren]]\n | after  = [[James Tomkinson]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ward, Robert}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n[[Category:Younger sons of earls]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Ward family|Robert]]\n[[Category:Worcestershire Yeomanry officers]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u